                  Uneven cooking is another prevalent problem that can arise in ovens. This issue often results from poor air circulation within the oven cavity, which can be due to a malfunctioning convection fan, blocked vents, or improper rack placement. Additionally, old or worn-out heating elements may fail to distribute heat evenly. To troubleshoot, ensure that the convection fan is working correctly and that vents are not obstructed. Rotating and repositioning food during cooking can also help, but if the problem persists, professional inspection may be necessary to identify and repair the underlying cause.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Door Seal Problems</h3>
                <p>
                  A faulty oven door seal can lead to heat escaping from the oven, causing inefficient cooking and increased energy consumption. The door gasket, typically made of rubber, can become worn, cracked, or loose over time, compromising the oven's ability to maintain a consistent internal temperature. This issue can also lead to longer preheating times and uneven cooking results. To address door seal problems, inspect the gasket regularly for signs of wear and tear, and replace it if necessary. Ensuring a tight seal when closing the oven door is crucial for optimal performance and energy efficiency.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
