                  <div class="FAQ">
                    <div class="fa">
                      <h3>What Are Factors That Determine Oven Repair Costs?</h3>
                    </div>

                    <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                    <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="questions">
                    <b>Type of oven</b>
                    <p>The oven repair cost can vary significantly depending on whether the oven is electric, gas, or a specialty oven types like a pizza or steam oven. Electric ovens tend to need less expensive repairs than gas ovens.</p>

                    <b>Extent of Damage</b>
                    <p>The severity of the damage or malfunction affects the complexity of the repair and, consequently, the appliance repair cost.</p>

                    <b>Parts Replacement</b>
                    <p>The cost of a replacement part varies depending on the brand, model, and availability of components needed for certain repairs.</p>

                    <b>Age of the oven</b>
                    <p>Older ovens over 10 years old may need costly repairs, as replacement parts can be harder to find. In some cases, it may be more cost-effective to replace an older oven rather than repair it.</p>

                    <b>Brand and Model</b>
                    <p>Different oven brands and models have varying complexities in their designs and components, influencing an average appliance repair cost.</p>

                    <b>Warranty Coverage</b>
                    <p>If the oven is still under warranty, some or all of the appliance repair costs may be covered, reducing the out-of-pocket expenses for the owner.</p>

                    <p>For minor repairs like replacing a light bulb or a knob, DIY appliance repair might be feasible. However, for anything more complex, it's safer and often more cost-effective to call a professional to avoid causing further damage.</p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="FAQ">
                    <div class="fa">
                      <h3>What is the average life expectancy of an Oven?</h3>
                    </div>

                    <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                    <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="questions">
                    <b>The average life expectancy of an oven is:</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Gas ovens can last an average of 15 years.</li>
                      <li>Electric ovens have a slightly shorter lifespan of around 13 years on average.</li>
                      <li>Built-in ovens, which require more construction and installation, typically last around the same 13-15 years as standalone ovens.</li>
                      <li>The quality and brand of the oven can also affect its lifespan, with higher-quality ovens from reputable brands generally lasting longer than cheaper models.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <b>To help extend the life of an oven, the key recommendations are:</b>
                    <ul>
                      <li>Regularly clean the oven interior, exterior, and door gaskets.</li>
                      <li>Avoid relying too heavily on the self-cleaning cycle, as the high temperatures can wear down the oven over time.</li>
                      <li>Have the oven professionally inspected and maintained annually.</li>
                      <li>Address any issues or malfunctions promptly rather than using a problematic oven.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>Following these maintenance tips, most ovens can reach their full 13-15-year lifespan, or even longer in the case of high-quality gas models.</p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="FAQ">
                    <div class="fa">
                      <h3>
                        Why does my stove work but not my oven?
                      </h3>
                    </div>

                    <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                    <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="questions">
                    <p>When your stove works but the oven breaks, there could be several reasons behind this issue:</p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>
                        <b>Gas Supply Issue: </b>If you have a gas oven, but the stove (which typically operates on gas) works fine while the oven does not, there might be an issue with the gas supply specifically to the oven. This could be due to a malfunctioning gas valve or a blockage in the oven's supply line.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Igniter Problems: </b>Gas ovens use an igniter to ignite the gas and create the flame necessary for heating. If the oven igniter is faulty or not working correctly, it can prevent the oven from heating up while allowing the stove burners to function normally.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Thermostat Malfunction:  </b>The oven thermostat regulates the temperature by controlling the flow of gas or electricity to the heating elements. If the thermostat is defective or out of calibration, it may not signal the oven to heat up properly even though the stove burners work fine.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Faulty Heating Element:  </b>Electric ovens rely on these to generate heat. If one or more of these elements is faulty or burned out, it can prevent the oven from heating while the stove continues to operate normally.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Control Panel Malfunctions:  </b>The control board serves as the "brain" of the oven, governing its various functions and settings. If the control board is malfunctioning or has failed, it may not send the necessary signals to the oven components to initiate the heating process.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Wiring Problems:  </b>An electric oven requires proper wiring to supply power to the heating elements and other components. If there are issues with the wiring, such as loose connections or damaged wires, it can disrupt the flow of electricity to the oven while allowing the stove to function.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <b>Internal Component Failures: </b>Various components within the oven, such as relays, switches, or sensors, can fail over time due to wear and tear or other factors. If any of these components fail, the oven may not heat correctly while the stove remains operational.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>While some oven and stove repairs may seem straightforward, it's essential to recognize that attempting DIY repairs can pose risks, especially if you're not familiar with appliance maintenance or lack the necessary skills and tools. Additionally, the cost to repair any mistakes made during the DIY process can outweigh the savings.</p>
                    <p>To determine the exact cause of the issue, it's recommended to have a qualified appliance technician inspect and diagnose your oven. They can identify the underlying problem and recommend the appropriate oven repair to restore its functionality.</p>
                  </div>

